  6-
  7-# Introduction
  8-
  9:OGNL as a language allows for the navigation of Java objects through a
  10-concise syntax that allows for specifying, where possible, symmetrically
  11-settable and gettable values. The language specifies a syntax that
  12-attempts to provide as high a level of abstraction as possible for
  13-navigating object graphs; this usually means specifying paths through
  14:and to JavaBeans properties, collection indices, etc. rather than
  15-directly accessing property getters and setters (collectively know as
  16-*accessors*).
  17-
  18-The normal usage of OGNL is to embed the language inside of other
  --
  71-
  72-## Extending OGNL
  73-
  74:OGNL expressions are not evaluated in a static environment, as Java
  75-programs are. Expressions are not compiled to bytecode at the expression
  76-level based on static class reachability. The same expression can have
  77-multiple paths through an object graph depending upon the root object
  78-specified and the dynamic results of the navigation. Objects that are
  --
  89-When navigating an OGNL expression many of the elements that are found
  90-are properties. Properties can be many things depending on the object
  91-being accessed. Most of the time these property names resolve to
  92:JavaBeans properties that conform to the set/get pattern. Other objects
  93-(such as `Map`) access properties as keyed values. Regardless of access
  94-methodology the OGNL syntax remains the same. Under the hood, however,
  95-there are `PropertyAccessor` objects that handle the conversion of
  96-property name to an actual access to an objects' properties.
  --
  105-
  106-You can set a property accessor on a class-by-class basis using
  107-OgnlRuntime.setPropertyAccessor(). There are default property accessors
  108:for `Object` (which uses JavaBeans patterns to extract properties) and
  109-`Map` (which uses the property name as a key).
  110-
  111-### Method Accessors
  112-
  --
  250-
  251-### Member Access
  252-
  253:Normally in Java the only members of a class (fields, methods) that can
  254-be accessed are the ones defined with public access. OGNL includes an
  255-interface that you can set globally (using
  256-`OgnlContext.setMemberAccessManager()`) that allows you to modify the
  257:runtime in Java 2 to allow access to private, protected and package
  258-protected fields and methods. Included in the OGNL package is the
  259-`DefaultMemberAccess` class. It contains a constructor that allows you
  260-to selectively lower the protection on any private, protected or package
  261:protected members` using the AccessibleObject` interface in Java2. The
  262-default class can be subclasses to select different objects for which
  263-accessibility is allowed.
  264-
  265-```java
  --
  276-When navigating a chain sometimes properties or methods will evaluate to
  277-null, causing subsequent properties or method calls to fail with
  278-`NullPointerException`s. Most of the time this behaviour is correct (as
  279:it is with Java), but sometimes you want to be able to dynamically
  280-substitute another object in place of `null`. The `NullHandler`
  281-interface allows you to specify on a class-by-class basis how nulls are
  282-handled within OGNL expressions. Implementing this interface allows you
  283-to intercept when methods return `null` and properties evaluate to
