  10-an expression and binding language for getting and setting properties of
  11-Java objects. Normally the same expression is used for both getting and
  12:setting the value of a property.
  13-
  14-We pronounce OGNL as a word, like the last syllables of a drunken
  --
  29-  [WebWork](http://sourceforge.net/projects/opensymphony),
  30-  [WebObjects](http://wonder.sourceforge.net/index.html)).
  31:- A more expressive replacement for the property-getting language used
  32-  by the Jakarta Commons BeanUtils package or JSTL's EL (which only
  33:  allow simple property navigation and rudimentary indexed
  34-  properties).
  35-
  --
  41-
  42-OGNL started out as a way to set up associations between UI components
  43:and controllers using property names. As the desire for more complicated
  44-associations grew, Drew Davidson created what he called KVCL, for
  45-Key-Value Coding Language, egged on by Luke Blanshard. Luke then
  --
  55-rich with features, but you don't generally need to worry about the more
  56-complicated parts of the language: the simple cases have remained that
  57:way. For example, to get at the name property of an object, the OGNL
  58:expression is simply name. To get at the text property of the object
  59:returned by the headline property, the OGNL expression is headline.text.
  60-
  61:What is a property? Roughly, an OGNL property is the same as a bean
  62:property, which means that a pair of get/set methods, or alternatively a
  63:field, defines a property (the full story is a bit more complicated,
  64-since properties differ for different kinds of objects; see below for a
  65-full explanation).
  --
  86-This expression follows these steps to evaluate:
  87-
  88:- extracts the name property of the initial, or root, object (which
  89-  the user provides to OGNL through the OGNL context)
  90:- calls the toCharArray() method on the resulting `String`
  91-- extracts the first character (the one at index 0) from the resulting
  92-  array
  93:- gets the numericValue property from that character (the character is
  94-  represented as a `Character` object, and the `Character` class has a
  95:  method called getNumericValue()).
  96-- calls toString() on the resulting `Integer` object. The final result
  97-  of this expression is the `String` returned by the last toString()
  --
  99-
  100-Note that this example can only be used to get a value from an object,
  101:not to set a value. Passing the above expression to the Ognl.setValue()
  102:method would cause an `InappropriateExpressionException` to be thrown,
  103:because the last link in the chain is neither a property name nor an
  104-array index.
  105-
  --
  131-
  132-OGNL treats different kinds of objects differently in its handling of
  133:property references. Maps treat all property references as element
  134:lookups or storage, with the property name as the key. Lists and arrays
  135:treat numeric properties similarly, with the property name as the index,
  136-but string properties the same way ordinary objects do. Ordinary objects
  137-(that is, all other kinds) only can handle string properties and do so
  138:by using "get" and "set" methods (or "is" and "set"), if the object has
  139-them, or a field with the given name otherwise.
  140-
  --
  157-## Indexing
  158-
  159:As discussed above, the "indexing" notation is actually just property
  160:reference, though a computed form of property reference rather than a
  161-constant one.
  162-
  --
  181-
  182-JavaBeans supports the concept of Indexed properties. Specifically this
  183:means that an object has a set of methods that follow the following
  184-pattern:
  185-
  --
  189-- public void setPropertyName(int index, PropertyType value)
  190-
  191:OGNL can interpret this and provide seamless access to the property
  192-through the indexing notation. References such as
  193-
  194-    someProperty[2]
  195-
  196:are automatically routed through the correct indexed property accessor
  197-(in the above case through `getSomeProperty(2)` or
  198:`setSomeProperty(2, value)`). If there is no indexed property accessor a
  199:property is found with the name `someProperty` and the index is applied
  200-to that.
  201-
  --
  205-arbitrary objects, not just integers as with JavaBeans Indexed
  206-Properties. When finding properties as candidates for object indexing,
  207:OGNL looks for patterns of methods with the following signature:
  208-
  209-- public PropertyType getPropertyName(IndexType index)
  --
  211-
  212-The PropertyType and IndexType must match each other in the
  213:corresponding set and get methods. An actual example of using Object
  214-Indexed Properties is with the Servlet API: the Session object has two
  215:methods for getting and setting arbitrary attributes:
  216-
  217-    public Object getAttribute(String name) public void setAttribute(String name, Object value)
  --
  223-## Calling Methods
  224-
  225:OGNL calls methods a little differently from the way Java does, because
  226:OGNL is interpreted and must choose the right method at run time, with
  227-no extra type information aside from the actual arguments supplied. OGNL
  228:always chooses the most specific method it can find whose types match
  229:the supplied arguments; if there are two or more methods that are
  230-equally specific and match the given arguments, one of them will be
  231-chosen arbitrarily.
  232-
  233-In particular, a null argument matches all non-primitive types, and so
  234:is most likely to result in an unexpected method being called.
  235-
  236:Note that the arguments to a method are separated by commas, and so the
  237-comma operator cannot be used unless it is enclosed in parentheses. For
